Why Modern Websites Rarely Write HTML Manually
In the early days of the web, developers wrote pages like this:
                                      <div class="product">
                                        <img src="phone.jpg">
                                        <h3>Phone</h3>
                                        <p>$499</p>
                                      </div>
                                      
                                      <div class="product">
                                        <img src="laptop.jpg">
                                        <h3>Laptop</h3>
                                        <p>$999</p>
                                      </div>

If a site had 1000 products, developers would have to repeat this 1000 times. That’s inefficient and hard to maintain.
So modern development uses templates, components, and data.

1️⃣ HTML Is Generated From Data
Instead of writing repeated HTML, developers store data like this:
[
  { "name": "Phone", "price": 499 },
  { "name": "Laptop", "price": 999 }
]

Then code automatically generates the HTML.
Example idea (simplified):

                            products.map(product => {
                              return `
                                <div class="product">
                                  <h3>${product.name}</h3>
                                  <p>$${product.price}</p>
                                </div>
                              `;
                            });
So the HTML is created dynamically.

2️⃣ Websites Use Components
Modern frameworks break the UI into reusable components.
Example component:
                            <div class="product-card">
                              <img src="image">
                              <h3>Product Name</h3>
                              <p>Price</p>
                            </div>
Instead of rewriting it, developers reuse it like:
                              <ProductCard />
                              <ProductCard />
                              <ProductCard />

Frameworks handle generating the HTML.
Common frameworks include:
React
Vue.js
Angular
These frameworks produce the HTML automatically.

3️⃣ The Browser Still Receives HTML
Even though developers write components or templates, the browser still receives normal HTML in the end.
Example result in the browser:
                                <div class="product-card">
                                  <h3>Phone</h3>
                                  <p>$499</p>
                                </div>
The frameworks just generate it behind the scenes.

4️⃣ Backend Servers Also Generate HTML
For many websites, the server builds HTML dynamically.
For example:
online stores
news sites
social media feeds

If you open a product page, the server inserts the product info into a template.
Example template:
                          <h1>{{product.name}}</h1>
                          <p>{{product.price}}</p>

The server replaces placeholders with real data.

Common backend tools include:
Node.js
Django
Laravel


5️⃣ Why This Approach Is Better
Efficiency
One component can generate thousands of items.

Maintainability
Change the component once → updates everywhere.

Dynamic content
Data from databases can automatically appear on the page.


